{"title_page": "Arthur Butler (bishop)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n\n'''Arthur Hamilton Butler''' {{post-nominals|MBE}} was an [[Irish people|Irish]] [[bishop]] in the [[Church of Ireland]] in the second half of the 20th century.<ref>\"A New History of Ireland\" Moody, T.M; Martin, F.X; Byrne, F.J; Cosgrove, F; Oxford:[[Oxford University Press]], 1976 {{ISBN|0-19-821745-5}}</ref>\n\nBorn on 8 March 1912 and educated at [[Friars School, Bangor]] <ref>[[Who's Who|\"Who was Who\"]] 1897-1990 London, [[A & C Black]], 1991 {{ISBN|0-7136-3457-X}}</ref>  and [[Trinity College, Dublin]],\nhe was [[ordained]] in 1936 and began his career as a [[curate]] at [[Monkstown, County Dublin]].<ref>[[Crockford's Clerical Directory]] 1940-41 Oxford, [[Oxford University Press|OUP]], 1941</ref>  London [[Curate|curacies]] at Christ Church, [[Crouch End]] and  [[Holy Trinity Brompton Church|Holy Trinity, Brompton]] were followed by six years as [[British Armed Forces|Army]] [[Chaplain]]. In 1945 he returned to [[Monkstown, County Dublin|Monkstown]] as incumbent, a post he held until his ordination to the [[episcopate]] as the 10th [[Bishop of Tuam, Killala and Achonry]] in 1958.<ref>[[The Times]], Thursday, 10 Apr 1958; pg. 10; Issue 54121; col D '' New Bishop Of Tuam''</ref> He was [[Translation (ecclesiastical)|translated]] to  be [[Bishop of Connor]] in 1969<ref>Fryde, E. B.; Greenway, D. E.; Porter, S.; Roy, I. (1996). Handbook of British Chronology (Third Edition, revised ed.). Cambridge: [[Cambridge University Press|CUP]]. {{ISBN|0-521-56350-X}}.</ref>  and retired in 1981. He died 6 July 1991.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Portal|Christianity}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-rel|ie}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[John Winthrop Crozier]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Bishop of Tuam, Killala and Achonry]]|years=1957 &ndash; 1969}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[John Coote Duggan]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Robert Cyril Hamilton Glover Elliott]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Bishop of Connor]]|years=1969 &ndash; 1981}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[William John McCappin]]}}\n{{end}}\n{{Bishops of Tuam, Killala, and Achonry }}\n{{Anglican bishop of Connor}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Butler, Arthur Hamilton}}\n[[Category:1912 births]]\n[[Category:People educated at Friars School, Bangor]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Trinity College Dublin]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Bishops of Tuam, Killala, and Achonry]]\n[[Category:20th-century Anglican bishops]]\n[[Category:Bishops of Connor]]\n[[Category:1991 deaths]]\n[[Category:Irish military chaplains]]\n[[Category:Royal Army Chaplains' Department officers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Irish clergy]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n\n'''Arthur Hamilton Butler''' [[MBE]] was an [[Irish people|Irish]] [[bishop]] in the [[Church of Ireland]] in the second half of the 20th century.<ref>\"A New History of Ireland\" Moody, T.M; Martin, F.X; Byrne, F.J; Cosgrove, F; Oxford:[[Oxford University Press]], 1976 {{ISBN|0-19-821745-5}}</ref>\n\nBorn on 8 March 1912 and educated at [[Friars School, Bangor]] <ref>[[Who's Who|\"Who was Who\"]] 1897-1990 London, [[A & C Black]], 1991 {{ISBN|0-7136-3457-X}}</ref>  and [[Trinity College, Dublin]],\nhe was [[ordained]] in 1936 and began his career as a [[curate]] at [[Monkstown, County Dublin]].<ref>[[Crockford's Clerical Directory]] 1940-41 Oxford, [[Oxford University Press|OUP]], 1941</ref>  London [[Curate|curacies]] at Christ Church, [[Crouch End]] and  [[Holy Trinity Brompton Church|Holy Trinity, Brompton]] were followed by six years as [[British Armed Forces|Army]] [[Chaplain]]. In 1945 he returned to [[Monkstown, County Dublin|Monkstown]] as incumbent, a post he held until his ordination to the [[episcopate]] as the 10th [[Bishop of Tuam, Killala and Achonry]] in 1958.<ref>[[The Times]], Thursday, 10 Apr 1958; pg. 10; Issue 54121; col D '' New Bishop Of Tuam''</ref> He was [[Translation (ecclesiastical)|translated]] to  be [[Bishop of Connor]] in 1969<ref>Fryde, E. B.; Greenway, D. E.; Porter, S.; Roy, I. (1996). Handbook of British Chronology (Third Edition, revised ed.). Cambridge: [[Cambridge University Press|CUP]]. {{ISBN|0-521-56350-X}}.</ref>  and retired in 1981. He died 6 July 1991.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Portal|Christianity}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-rel|ie}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[John Winthrop Crozier]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Bishop of Tuam, Killala and Achonry]]|years=1957 &ndash; 1969}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[John Coote Duggan]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Robert Cyril Hamilton Glover Elliott]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Bishop of Connor]]|years=1969 &ndash; 1981}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[William John McCappin]]}}\n{{end}}\n{{Bishops of Tuam, Killala, and Achonry }}\n{{Anglican bishop of Connor}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Butler, Arthur Hamilton}}\n[[Category:1912 births]]\n[[Category:People educated at Friars School, Bangor]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Trinity College Dublin]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Bishops of Tuam, Killala, and Achonry]]\n[[Category:20th-century Anglican bishops]]\n[[Category:Bishops of Connor]]\n[[Category:1991 deaths]]\n[[Category:Irish military chaplains]]\n[[Category:Royal Army Chaplains' Department officers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Irish clergy]]\n", "name_user": "Paradoctor", "label": "safe", "comment": "dab", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arthur_Butler_(bishop)"}
